ory J. Goodall"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 679889, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jeffrey E. Green"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1126248, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Min Zhu"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1072579, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Chang-Hee Kim"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 229695, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jiuyong Li"}), :year 2010, :venue "Bioinformatics", :ncit 20, :string "Identifying functional miRNA-mRNA regulatory modules with correspondence latent dirichlet allocation.. ", :doc-id "Identifying functional miRNA-mRNA regulatory modules with correspondence latent dirichlet allocation. 2010  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  "}, 303143 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 303143, :key "conf/icdm/ShafieiM06", :title "Latent Dirichlet Co-Clustering.", :abstract "We present a generative model for simultaneously clustering documents and terms. Our model is a four-level hierarchical Bayesian model, in which each document is modeled as a random mixture of document topics , where each topic is a distribution over some segments of the text. Each of these segments in the document can be modeled as a mixture of word topics where each topic is a distribution over words. We present efficient approximate inference techniques based on Markov Chain Monte Carlo method and a Moment-Matching algorithm for empirical Bayes parameter estimation. We report results in document modeling, document and term clustering, comparing to other topic models, Clustering and Co-Clustering algorithms including Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA), Model-based Overlapping Clustering (MOC), Model-based Overlapping Co-Clustering (MOCC) and Information-Theoretic Co-Clustering (ITCC).", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 334867, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "M. Mahdi Shafiei"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 641371, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Evangelos E. Milios"}), :year 2006, :venue "ICDM", :ncit 32, :string "Latent Dirichlet Co-Clustering.. We present a generative model for simultaneously clustering documents and terms. Our model is a four-level hierarchical Bayesian model, in which each document is modeled as a random mixture of document topics , where each topic is a distribution over some segments of the text. Each of these segments in the document can be modeled as a mixture of word topics where each topic is a distribution over words. We present efficient approximate inference techniques based on Markov Chain Monte Carlo method and a Moment-Matching algorithm for empirical Bayes parameter estimation. We report results in document modeling, document and term clustering, comparing to other topic models, Clustering and Co-Clustering algorithms including Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA), Model-based Overlapping Clustering (MOC), Model-based Overlapping Co-Clustering (MOCC) and Information-Theoretic Co-Clustering (ITCC).", :doc-id "Latent Dirichlet Co-Clustering. 2006  ,  "}, 257351 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 257351, :key "conf/humo/WangSM07", :title "Semi-Latent Dirichlet Allocation: A Hierarchical Model for Human Action Recognition.", :abstract "We propose a new method for human action recognition from video sequences using latent topic models. Video sequences are represented by a novel \"bag-of-words\" representation, where each frame corresponds to a \"word\". The major difference between our model and previous latent topic models for recognition problems in computer vision is that, our model is trained in a \"semi-supervised\" way. Our model has several advantages over other similar models. First of all, the training is much easier due to the decoupling of the model parameters. Secondly, it naturally solves the problem of how to choose the appropriate number of latent topics. Thirdly, it achieves much better performance by utilizing the information provided by the class labels in the training set. We present action classification and irregularity detection results, and show improvement over previous methods.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 731259, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yang Wang"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1482291, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Payam Sabzmeydani"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1197992, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Greg Mori"}), :year 2007, :venue "Workshop on Human Motion", :ncit 39, :string "Semi-Latent Dirichlet Allocation: A Hierarchical Model for Human Action Recognition.. We propose a new method for human action recognition from video sequences using latent topic models. Video sequences are represented by a novel \"bag-of-words\" representation, where each frame corresponds to a \"word\". The major difference between our model and previous latent topic models for recognition problems in computer vision is that, our model is trained in a \"semi-supervised\" way. Our model has several advantages over other similar models. First of all, the training is much easier due to the decoupling of the model parameters. Secondly, it naturally solves the problem of how to choose the appropriate number of latent topics. Thirdly, it achieves much better performance by utilizing the information provided by the class labels in the training set. We present action classification and irregularity detection results, and show improvement over previous methods.", :doc-id "Semi-Latent Dirichlet Allocation: A Hierarchical Model for Human Action Recognition. 2007  ,  ,  "}, 1269415 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1269415, :key "journals/corr/abs-0909-4603", :title "Scalable Inference for Latent Dirichlet Allocation", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1094364, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "James Petterson"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 376169, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Tibério S. Caetano"}), :year 2009, :venue "CoRR", :ncit 0, :string "Scalable Inference for Latent Dirichlet Allocation. ", :doc-id "Scalable Inference for Latent Dirichlet Allocation 2009  ,  "}, 839495 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 839495, :key "journals/datamine/GirolamiK05", :title "Sequential Activity Profiling: Latent Dirichlet Allocation of Markov Chains.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1366376, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Mark Girolami"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 863070, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Ata Kabán"}), :year 2005, :venue "Data Min. Knowl. Discov.", :ncit 21, :string "Sequential Activity Profiling: Latent Dirichlet Allocation of Markov Chains.. ", :doc-id "Sequential Activity Profiling: Latent Dirichlet Allocation of Markov Chains. 2005  ,  "}, 2950023 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2950023, :key "conf/naacl/WilsonC10", :title "Term Weighting Schemes for Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1612181, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Andrew T. Wilson"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 99143, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Peter A. Chew"}), :year 2010, :venue "HLT-NAACL", :ncit 6, :string "Term Weighting Schemes for Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. ", :doc-id "Term Weighting Schemes for Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2010  ,  "}, 2942919 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2942919, :key "conf/dmin/ChoiL10", :title "Document Indexing by Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 782890, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "In-Chan Choi"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 802159, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jae-Sung Lee"}), :year 2010, :venue "DMIN", :ncit 0, :string "Document Indexing by Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. ", :doc-id "Document Indexing by Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2010  ,  "}, 2782664 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2782664, :key "conf/das/BhardwajRSGS10", :title "Latent Dirichlet allocation based writer identification in offline handwriting.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 605924, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Anurag Bhardwaj"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1544173, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Manavender Reddy"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1231689, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Srirangaraj Setlur"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 292639, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Venu Govindaraju"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 183321, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Ramachandrula Sitaram"}), :year 2010, :venue "Document Analysis Systems", :ncit 6, :string "Latent Dirichlet allocation based writer identification in offline handwriting.. ", :doc-id "Latent Dirichlet allocation based writer identification in offline handwriting. 2010  ,  ,  ,  ,  "}, 170568 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 170568, :key "conf/ecir/BolelliEG09", :title "Topic and Trend Detection in Text Collections Using Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract "Algorithms that enable the process of automatically mining distinct topics in document collections have become increasingly important due to their applications in many fields and the extensive growth of the number of documents in various domains. In this paper, we propose a generative model based on latent Dirichlet allocation that integrates the temporal ordering of the documents into the generative process in an iterative fashion. The document collection is divided into time segments where the discovered topics in each segment is propagated to influence the topic discovery in the subsequent time segments. Our experimental results on a collection of academic papers from CiteSeer repository show that segmented topic model can effectively detect distinct topics and their evolution over time.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 384482, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Levent Bolelli"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 559416, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Seyda Ertekin"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 239072, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "C. Lee Giles"}), :year 2009, :venue "ECIR", :ncit 12, :string "Topic and Trend Detection in Text Collections Using Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. Algorithms that enable the process of automatically mining distinct topics in document collections have become increasingly important due to their applications in many fields and the extensive growth of the number of documents in various domains. In this paper, we propose a generative model based on latent Dirichlet allocation that integrates the temporal ordering of the documents into the generative process in an iterative fashion. The document collection is divided into time segments where the discovered topics in each segment is propagated to influence the topic discovery in the subsequent time segments. Our experimental results on a collection of academic papers from CiteSeer repository show that segmented topic model can effectively detect distinct topics and their evolution over time.", :doc-id "Topic and Trend Detection in Text Collections Using Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2009  ,  ,  "}, 3062504 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3062504, :key "journals/cai/Yingjun11", :title "The Variant of Latent Dirichlet Allocation for Natural Scene Classification.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14117668, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "T. Yingjun"}), :year 2011, :venue "Computing and Informatics", :ncit 0, :string "The Variant of Latent Dirichlet Allocation for Natural Scene Classification.. ", :doc-id "The Variant of Latent Dirichlet Allocation for Natural Scene Classification. 2011  "}, 3635016 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3635016, :key "conf/asunam/DokoohakiM12", :title "Mining Divergent Opinion Trust Networks through Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 634403, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Nima Dokoohaki"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1179257, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Mihhail Matskin"}), :year 2012, :venue "ASONAM", :ncit 1, :string "Mining Divergent Opinion Trust Networks through Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. ", :doc-id "Mining Divergent Opinion Trust Networks through Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2012  ,  "}, 2809257 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2809257, :key "conf/pakdd/ArunSMM10", :title "On Finding the Natural Number of Topics with Latent Dirichlet Allocation: Some Observations.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 58690, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "R. Arun"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 823856, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "V. Suresh"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 210293, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "C. E. Veni Madhavan"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1554062, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "M. N. Narasimha Murthy"}), :year 2010, :venue "PAKDD (1)", :ncit 8, :string "On Finding the Natural Number of Topics with Latent Dirichlet Allocation: Some Observations.. ", :doc-id "On Finding the Natural Number of Topics with Latent Dirichlet Allocation: Some Observations. 2010  ,  ,  ,  "}, 734665 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 734665, :key "conf/indiaSE/RamaSH08", :title "Mining business topics in source code using latent dirichlet allocation.", :abstract "One of the difficulties in maintaining a large software system is the absence of documented business domain topics and correlation between these domain topics and source code. Without such a correlation, people without any prior application knowledge would find it hard to comprehend the functionality of the system. Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA), a statistical model, has emerged as a popular technique for discovering topics in large text document corpus. But its applicability in extracting business domain topics from source code has not been explored so far. This paper investigates LDA in the context of comprehending large software systems and proposes a human assisted approachbased on LDA for extracting domain topics from source code. This method has been applied on a number of open source and proprietary systems. Preliminary results indicate that LDA is able to identify some of the domain topics and isa satisfactory starting point for further manual refinement of topics", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1018880, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Girish Maskeri Rama"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 115936, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Santonu Sarkar"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 379509, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Kenneth Heafield"}), :year 2008, :venue "ISEC", :ncit 54, :string "Mining business topics in source code using latent dirichlet allocation.. One of the difficulties in maintaining a large software system is the absence of documented business domain topics and correlation between these domain topics and source code. Without such a correlation, people without any prior application knowledge would find it hard to comprehend the functionality of the system. Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA), a statistical model, has emerged as a popular technique for discovering topics in large text document corpus. But its applicability in extracting business domain topics from source code has not been explored so far. This paper investigates LDA in the context of comprehending large software systems and proposes a human assisted approachbased on LDA for extracting domain topics from source code. This method has been applied on a number of open source and proprietary systems. Preliminary results indicate that LDA is able to identify some of the domain topics and isa satisfactory starting point for further manual refinement of topics", :doc-id "Mining business topics in source code using latent dirichlet allocation. 2008  ,  ,  "}, 2947529 #search_api.searc