 where K is the number of topics in the model. Our proposed method draws equivalent samples but requires on average significantly less then K operations per sample. On real-word corpora FastLDA can be as much as 8 times faster than the standard collapsed Gibbs sampler for LDA. No approximations are necessary, and we show that our fast sampling scheme produces exactly the same results as the standard (but slower) sampling scheme. Experiments on four real world data sets demonstrate speedups for a wide range of collection sizes. For the PubMed collection of over 8 million documents with a required computation time of 6 CPU months for LDA, our speedup of 5.7 can save 5 CPU months of computation.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 429539, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Ian Porteous"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1014050, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "David Newman"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 175258, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Alexander T. Ihler"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 491097, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Arthur Asuncion"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 218377, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Padhraic Smyth"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 50468, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Max Welling"}), :year 2008, :venue "KDD", :ncit 86, :string "Fast collapsed gibbs sampling for latent dirichlet allocation.. In this paper we introduce a novel collapsed Gibbs sampling method for the widely used latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA) model. Our new method results in significant speedups on real world text corpora. Conventional Gibbs sampling schemes for LDA require O(K) operations per sample where K is the number of topics in the model. Our proposed method draws equivalent samples but requires on average significantly less then K operations per sample. On real-word corpora FastLDA can be as much as 8 times faster than the standard collapsed Gibbs sampler for LDA. No approximations are necessary, and we show that our fast sampling scheme produces exactly the same results as the standard (but slower) sampling scheme. Experiments on four real world data sets demonstrate speedups for a wide range of collection sizes. For the PubMed collection of over 8 million documents with a required computation time of 6 CPU months for LDA, our speedup of 5.7 can save 5 CPU months of computation.", :doc-id "Fast collapsed gibbs sampling for latent dirichlet allocation. 2008  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  "}, 3751625 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3751625, :key "conf/dateso/CamprJ13", :title "Comparative Summarization via Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14191101, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Michal Campr"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 50202, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Karel Jezek"}), :year 2013, :venue "DATESO", :ncit 0, :string "Comparative Summarization via Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. ", :doc-id "Comparative Summarization via Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2013  ,  "}, 3365833 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3365833, :key "journals/kais/DuBJC12", :title "Sequential latent Dirichlet allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 333478, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Lan Du"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1075369, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Wray L. Buntine"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 815715, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Huidong Jin"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 113075, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Changyou Chen"}), :year 2012, :venue "Knowl. Inf. Syst.", :ncit 4, :string "Sequential latent Dirichlet allocation.. ", :doc-id "Sequential latent Dirichlet allocation. 2012  ,  ,  ,  "}, 2820394 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2820394, :key "conf/prib/PerinaLMB10", :title "Biologically-aware Latent Dirichlet Allocation (BaLDA) for the Classification of Expression Microarray.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1478114, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Alessandro Perina"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1489368, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Pietro Lovato"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 217893, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Vittorio Murino"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1231147, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Manuele Bicego"}), :year 2010, :venue "PRIB", :ncit 8, :string "Biologically-aware Latent Dirichlet Allocation (BaLDA) for the Classification of Expression Microarray.. ", :doc-id "Biologically-aware Latent Dirichlet Allocation (BaLDA) for the Classification of Expression Microarray. 2010  ,  ,  ,  "}, 3395306 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3395306, :key "journals/pr/VretosNP12", :title "Video fingerprinting using Latent Dirichlet Allocation and facial images.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 917344, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Nicholas Vretos"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1043356, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Nikos Nikolaidis"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 175341, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Ioannis Pitas"}), :year 2012, :venue "Pattern Recognition", :ncit 0, :string "Video fingerprinting using Latent Dirichlet Allocation and facial images.. ", :doc-id "Video fingerprinting using Latent Dirichlet Allocation and facial images. 2012  ,  ,  "}, 2897387 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2897387, :key "conf/adma/TuL10", :title "Topic-Based User Segmentation for Online Advertising with Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1586147, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Songgao Tu"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1586148, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Chaojun Lu"}), :year 2010, :venue "Principles and Applications of Distributed Event-Based Systems", :ncit 0, :string "Topic-Based User Segmentation for Online Advertising with Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. ", :doc-id "Topic-Based User Segmentation for Online Advertising with Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2010  ,  "}, 1237515 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1237515, :key "conf/airs/Ha-ThucS09", :title "A Latent Dirichlet Framework for Relevance Modeling.", :abstract "Relevance-based language models operate by estimating the probabilities of observing words in documents relevant (or pseudo relevant) to a topic. However, these models assume that if a document is relevant to a topic, then all tokens in the document are relevant to that topic. This could limit model robustness and effectiveness. In this study, we propose a Latent Dirichlet relevance model, which relaxes this assumption. Our approach derives from current research on Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) topic models. LDA has been extensively explored, especially for discovering a set of topics from a corpus. LDA itself, however, has a limitation that is also addressed in our work. Topics generated by LDA from a corpus are synthetic, i.e., they do not necessarily correspond to topics identified by humans for the same corpus. In contrast, our model explicitly considers the relevance relationships between documents and given topics (queries). Thus unlike standard LDA, our model is directly applicable to goals such as relevance feedback for query modification and text classification, where topics (classes and queries) are provided upfront. Thus although the focus of our paper is on improving relevance-based language models, in effect our approach bridges relevance-based language models and LDA addressing limitations of both.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1524517, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Viet Ha-Thuc"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1060058, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Padmini Srinivasan"}), :year 2009, :venue "AIRS", :ncit 2, :string "A Latent Dirichlet Framework for Relevance Modeling.. Relevance-based language models operate by estimating the probabilities of observing words in documents relevant (or pseudo relevant) to a topic. However, these models assume that if a document is relevant to a topic, then all tokens in the document are relevant to that topic. This could limit model robustness and effectiveness. In this study, we propose a Latent Dirichlet relevance model, which relaxes this assumption. Our approach derives from current research on Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) topic models. LDA has been extensively explored, especially for discovering a set of topics from a corpus. LDA itself, however, has a limitation that is also addressed in our work. Topics generated by LDA from a corpus are synthetic, i.e., they do not necessarily correspond to topics identified by humans for the same corpus. In contrast, our model explicitly considers the relevance relationships between documents and given topics (queries). Thus unlike standard LDA, our model is directly applicable to goals such as relevance feedback for query modification and text classification, where topics (classes and queries) are provided upfront. Thus although the focus of our paper is on improving relevance-based language models, in effect our approach bridges relevance-based language models and LDA addressing limitations of both.", :doc-id "A Latent Dirichlet Framework for Relevance Modeling. 2009  ,  "}, 984971 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 984971, :key "journals/jmlr/BleiNJ03", :title "Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract "We describe latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA), a generative probabilistic model for collections of discrete data such as text corpora. LDA is a three-level hierarchical Bayesian model, in which each item of a collection is modeled as a finite mixture over an underlying set of topics. Each topic is, in turn, modeled as an infinite mixture over an underlying set of topic probabilities. In the context of text modeling, the topic probabilities provide an explicit representation of a document. We present efficient approximate inference techniques based on variational methods and an EM algorithm for empirical Bayes parameter estimation. We report results in document modeling, text classification, and collaborative filtering, comparing to a mixture of unigrams model and the probabilistic LSI model.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 264481, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "David M. Blei"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 123223, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Andrew Y. Ng"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 221919, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Michael I. Jordan"}), :year 2003, :venue "Journal of Machine Learning Research", :ncit 6625, :string "Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. We describe latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA), a generative probabilistic model for collections of discrete data such as text corpora. LDA is a three-level hierarchical Bayesian model, in which each item of a collection is modeled as a finite mixture over an underlying set of topics. Each topic is, in turn, modeled as an infinite mixture over an underlying set of topic probabilities. In the context of text modeling, the topic probabilities provide an explicit representation of a document. We present efficient approximate inference techniques based on variational methods and an EM algorithm for empirical Bayes parameter estimation. We report results in document modeling, text classification, and collaborative filtering, comparing to a mixture of unigrams model and the probabilistic LSI model.", :doc-id "Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2003  ,  ,  "}, 701644 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 701644, :key "conf/airweb/BiroSB08", :title "Latent dirichlet allocation in web spam filtering.", :abstract "Latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA) (Blei, Ng, Jordan 2003) is a fully generative statistical language model on the content and topics of a corpus of documents. In this paper we apply a modification of LDA, the novel multi-corpus LDA technique for web spam classification. We create a bag-of-words document for every Web site and run LDA both on the corpus of sites labeled as spam and as non-spam. In this way collections of spam and non-spam topics are created in the training phase. In the test phase we take the union of these collections, and an unseen site is deemed spam if its total spam topic probability is above a threshold. As far as we know, this is the first web retrieval application of LDA. We test this method on the UK2007-WEBSPAM corpus, and reach a relative improvement of 11% in F-measure by a logistic regression based combination with strong link and content baseline classifiers.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1532256, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "István Bíró"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 559961, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jácint Szabó"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 510808, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "András A. Benczúr"}), :year 2008, :venue "AIRWeb", :ncit 0, :string "Latent dirichlet allocation in web spam filtering.. Latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA) (Blei, Ng, Jordan 2003) is a fully generative statistical language model on the content and topics of a corpus of documents. In this paper we apply a modification of LDA, the novel multi-corpus LDA technique for web spam classification. We create a bag-of-words document for every Web site and run LDA both on the corpus of sites labeled as spam and as non-spam. In this way collections of spam and non-spam topics are created in the training phase. In the test phase we take the union of these collections, and an unseen site is deemed spam if its total spam topic probability is above a threshold. As far as we know, this is the first web retrieval application of LDA. We test this method on the UK2007-WEBSPAM corpus, and reach a relative improvement of 11% in F-measure by a logistic regression based combination with strong link and content baseline classifiers.", :doc-id "Latent dirichlet allocation in web spam filtering. 2008  ,  ,  "}, 3241676 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3241676, :key "conf/nips/YanXQ09", :title "Parallel Inference for Latent Dirichlet Allocation on Graphics Processing Units.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1054019, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Feng Yan"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 520546, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Ningyi Xu"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 259784, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yuan Qi"}), :year 2009, :venue "NIPS", :ncit 25, :string "Parallel Inference for Latent Dirichlet Allocation on Graphics Processing Units.. ", :doc-id "Parallel Inference for Latent Dirichlet Allocation on Graphics Processing Units. 2009  ,  ,  "}, 3443949 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3443949, :key "conf/nips/SontagR11", :title "Complexity of Inference in Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1348351, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "David Sontag"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14298222, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Dan Roy"}), :year 2011, :venue "NIPS", :ncit 0, :string "Complexity of Inference in Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. ", :doc-id "Complexity of Inference in Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2011  ,  "}, 3096045 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3096045, :key "journals/tist/LiuZCS11", :title "PLDA+: Parallel latent dirichlet allocation with data placement and pipeline processing.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 926689, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Zhiyuan Liu"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 839203, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yuzhou Zhang"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 4853, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Edward Y. Chang"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 711065, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Maosong Sun"