opic model, we are able to obtain a fitted Dirichlet parameter that provides the maximum likelihood for the document set. In this article, we examine the sensitivity of LDA with respect to the Dirichlet parameter when used for Information retrieval. We compare the topic model computation times, storage requirements and retrieval precision of fitted LDA to LDA with a uniform Dirichlet prior. The results show there there is no significant benefit of using fitted LDA over the LDA with a constant Dirichlet parameter, hence showing that LDA is insensitive with respect to the Dirichlet parameter when used for Information retrieval.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 216499, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Laurence A. F. Park"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1206953, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Kotagiri Ramamohanarao"}), :year 2009, :venue "ECML/PKDD (2)", :ncit 7, :string "The Sensitivity of Latent Dirichlet Allocation for Information Retrieval.. It has been shown that the use of topic models for Information retrieval provides an increase in precision when used in the appropriate form. Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) is a generative topic model that allows us to model documents using a Dirichlet prior. Using this topic model, we are able to obtain a fitted Dirichlet parameter that provides the maximum likelihood for the document set. In this article, we examine the sensitivity of LDA with respect to the Dirichlet parameter when used for Information retrieval. We compare the topic model computation times, storage requirements and retrieval precision of fitted LDA to LDA with a uniform Dirichlet prior. The results show there there is no significant benefit of using fitted LDA over the LDA with a constant Dirichlet parameter, hence showing that LDA is insensitive with respect to the Dirichlet parameter when used for Information retrieval.", :doc-id "The Sensitivity of Latent Dirichlet Allocation for Information Retrieval. 2009  ,  "}, 3469582 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3469582, :key "journals/cmmm/Yang12", :title "Identification of Novel Type III Effectors Using Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 756242, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yang Yang"}), :year 2012, :venue "Comp. Math. Methods in Medicine", :ncit 1, :string "Identification of Novel Type III Effectors Using Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. ", :doc-id "Identification of Novel Type III Effectors Using Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2012  "}, 517934 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 517934, :key "conf/nips/NewmanASW07", :title "Distributed Inference for Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1014050, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "David Newman"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 491097, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Arthur Asuncion"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 218377, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Padhraic Smyth"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 50468, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Max Welling"}), :year 2007, :venue "NIPS", :ncit 98, :string "Distributed Inference for Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. ", :doc-id "Distributed Inference for Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2007  ,  ,  ,  "}, 1254415 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1254415, :key "conf/pkdd/BiroS09", :title "Latent Dirichlet Allocation for Automatic Document Categorization.", :abstract "In this paper we introduce and evaluate a technique for applying latent Dirichlet allocation to supervised semantic categorization of documents. In our setup, for every category an own collection of topics is assigned, and for a labeled training document only topics from its category are sampled. Thus, compared to the classical LDA that processes the entire corpus in one, we essentially build separate LDA models for each category with the category-specific topics, and then these topic collections are put together to form a unified LDA model. For an unseen document the inferred topic distribution gives an estimation how much the document fits into the category.We use this method for Web document classification. Our key results are 46% decrease in 1-AUC value in classification accuracy over tf.idf with SVM and 43% over the plain LDA baseline with SVM. Using a careful vocabulary selection method and a heuristic which handles the effect that similar topics may arise in distinct categories the improvement is 83% over tf.idf with SVM and 82% over LDA with SVM in 1-AUC.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1532256, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "István Bíró"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 559961, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jácint Szabó"}), :year 2009, :venue "ECML/PKDD (2)", :ncit 1, :string "Latent Dirichlet Allocation for Automatic Document Categorization.. In this paper we introduce and evaluate a technique for applying latent Dirichlet allocation to supervised semantic categorization of documents. In our setup, for every category an own collection of topics is assigned, and for a labeled training document only topics from its category are sampled. Thus, compared to the classical LDA that processes the entire corpus in one, we essentially build separate LDA models for each category with the category-specific topics, and then these topic collections are put together to form a unified LDA model. For an unseen document the inferred topic distribution gives an estimation how much the document fits into the category.We use this method for Web document classification. Our key results are 46% decrease in 1-AUC value in classification accuracy over tf.idf with SVM and 43% over the plain LDA baseline with SVM. Using a careful vocabulary selection method and a heuristic which handles the effect that similar topics may arise in distinct categories the improvement is 83% over tf.idf with SVM and 82% over LDA with SVM in 1-AUC.", :doc-id "Latent Dirichlet Allocation for Automatic Document Categorization. 2009  ,  "}, 3781615 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3781615, :key "conf/ai/RazaviIBB13", :title "General Topic Annotation in Social Networks: A Latent Dirichlet Allocation Approach.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 356312, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Amir Hossein Razavi"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 46934, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Diana Inkpen"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14452063, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Dmitry Brusilovsky"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14452064, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Lana Bogouslavski"}), :year 2013, :venue "Canadian Conference on AI", :ncit 0, :string "General Topic Annotation in Social Networks: A Latent Dirichlet Allocation Approach.. ", :doc-id "General Topic Annotation in Social Networks: A Latent Dirichlet Allocation Approach. 2013  ,  ,  ,  "}, 1248080 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1248080, :key "conf/icmla/LinsteadLB08", :title "An Application of Latent Dirichlet Allocation to Analyzing Software Evolution.", :abstract "We develop and apply unsupervised statistical topic models, in particular Latent Dirichlet Allocation, to identify functional components of source code and study their evolution over multiple project versions. We present results for two large, open source Java projects, Eclipse and Argo UML, which are well-known and well-studied within the software mining community. Our results demonstrate the effectiveness of probabilistic topic models in automatically summarizing the temporal dynamics of software concerns, with direct application to project management and program understanding. In addition to detecting the emergence of topics on the release timeline which represent integration points for key source code functionality, our techniques can also be used to pinpoint refactoring events in the underlying software design, as well as to identify general programming concepts whose prevalence is dependent only of the size of the code base to be analyzed. Complete results are available from our supplementary materials website at http://sourcerer.ics.uci.edu/icmla2008/software_evolution.html.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 534345, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Erik Linstead"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 296742, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Cristina Videira Lopes"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1308756, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Pierre Baldi"}), :year 2008, :venue "ICMLA", :ncit 22, :string "An Application of Latent Dirichlet Allocation to Analyzing Software Evolution.. We develop and apply unsupervised statistical topic models, in particular Latent Dirichlet Allocation, to identify functional components of source code and study their evolution over multiple project versions. We present results for two large, open source Java projects, Eclipse and Argo UML, which are well-known and well-studied within the software mining community. Our results demonstrate the effectiveness of probabilistic topic models in automatically summarizing the temporal dynamics of software concerns, with direct application to project management and program understanding. In addition to detecting the emergence of topics on the release timeline which represent integration points for key source code functionality, our techniques can also be used to pinpoint refactoring events in the underlying software design, as well as to identify general programming concepts whose prevalence is dependent only of the size of the code base to be analyzed. Complete results are available from our supplementary materials website at http://sourcerer.ics.uci.edu/icmla2008/software_evolution.html.", :doc-id "An Application of Latent Dirichlet Allocation to Analyzing Software Evolution. 2008  ,  ,  "}, 1046673 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1046673, :key "journals/prl/XingG07", :title "Employing Latent Dirichlet Allocation for fraud detection in telecommunications.", :abstract "Fraud detection in the telecommunications industry requires the identification of a small fraction of fraudulent calls from the high volume of call traffic. This presents a significant research challenge in the design of efficient and effective algorithms to combat telecommunications fraud. This paper employs Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) to build user profile signatures and assumes that any significant unexplainable deviations from the normal activity of an individual user is strongly correlated with fraudulent activity. The user activity is represented as a probability distribution over call features which surmises the user's calling behaviour. This probability distribution is derived from LDA which can accurately describe user profiles by combining different classes of distributions. To score calls we compare the likelihood of the user generating a call versus a fraudster generating the same call. Our experiments demonstrate that using such a probability distribution and employing even a rough profile of a fraudster's activity ameliorates the detection of fraudulent calls. Our method is computationally efficient and can scale up to a realistic real time detection.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 780592, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Dongshan Xing"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1366376, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Mark Girolami"}), :year 2007, :venue "Pattern Recognition Letters", :ncit 33, :string "Employing Latent Dirichlet Allocation for fraud detection in telecommunications.. Fraud detection in the telecommunications industry requires the identification of a small fraction of fraudulent calls from the high volume of call traffic. This presents a significant research challenge in the design of efficient and effective algorithms to combat telecommunications fraud. This paper employs Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) to build user profile signatures and assumes that any significant unexplainable deviations from the normal activity of an individual user is strongly correlated with fraudulent activity. The user activity is represented as a probability distribution over call features which surmises the user's calling behaviour. This probability distribution is derived from LDA which can accurately describe user profiles by combining different classes of distributions. To score calls we compare the likelihood of the user generating a call versus a fraudster generating the same call. Our experiments demonstrate that using such a probability distribution and employing even a rough profile of a fraudster's activity ameliorates the detection of fraudulent calls. Our method is computationally efficient and can scale up to a realistic real time detection.", :doc-id "Employing Latent Dirichlet Allocation for fraud detection in telecommunications. 2007  ,  "}, 3173841 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3173841, :key "conf/icassp/LiLZ11", :title "Hierarchical Latent Dirichlet Allocation models for realistic action recognition.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1443480, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Heping Li"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1091237, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jie Liu"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 144129, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Shuwu Zhang"}), :year 2011, :venue "ICASSP", :ncit 0, :string "Hierarchical Latent Dirichlet Allocation models for realistic action recognition.. ", :doc-id "Hierarchical Latent Dirichlet Allocation models for realistic action recognition. 2011  ,  ,  "}, 596497 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 596497, :key "conf/sigir/AroraR08", :title "Latent dirichlet allocation based multi-document summarization.", :abstract "Extraction based Multi-Document Summarization Algorithms consist of choosing sentences from the documents using some weighting mechanism and combining them into a summary. In this article we use Latent Dirichlet Allocation to capture the events being covered by the documents and form the summary with sentences representing these different events. Our approach is distinguished from existing approaches in that we use mixture models to capture the topics and pick up the sentences without paying attention to the details of grammar and structure of the documents. Finally we present the evaluation of the algorithms on the DUC 2002 Corpus multi-document summarization tasks using the ROUGE evaluator to evaluate the summaries. Compared to DUC 2002 winners, our algorithms gave significantly better ROUGE-1 recall measures.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1044178, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Rachit Arora"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 657054, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Balaraman Ravindran"}), :year 2008, :venue "AND", :ncit 39, :string "Latent dirichlet allocation based multi-document summarization.. Extraction based Multi-Document Summarization Algorithms consist of choosing sentences from the documents using some weighting mechanism and combining them into a summary. In this article we use Latent Dirichlet Allocation to capture the events being covered by the documents and form the summary with sentences representing these different events. Our approach is distinguished from existing approaches in that we use mixture models to capture the topics and pick up the sentences without paying attention to the details of grammar and structure of the documents. Finally we present the evaluation of the algorithms on the DUC 2002 Corpus multi-document summarization tasks using the ROUGE evaluator to evaluate the summaries. Compared to DUC 2002 winners, our algorithms gave significantly better ROUGE-1 recall measures.", :doc-id "Latent dirichlet allocation based multi-document summarization. 2008  ,  "}, 303665 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 303665, :key "conf/icdm/ShenSS08", :title "Collective Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract "In this paper, we propose a new variant of Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA): Collective LDA (C-LDA), for multiple corpora modeling. C-LDA combines multiple corpora during learning such that it can transfer knowledge from one corpus to another; meanwhile it keeps a discriminative node which represents the corpus ID to constrain the learned topics in each corpus. Compared with LDA locally applied to the target corpus, C-LDA results in refined topic-word distribution, while compared with applying LDA globally and straightforwardly to the combined corpus, C-LDA keeps each topic only for one corpus. We demonstrate that C-LDA has improved performance with these advantages by experiments on several benchmark document data sets.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1203487, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Zhiyong Shen"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 450433, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jun Sun"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 249734, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yi-Dong Shen"}), :year 2008, :venue "ICDM", :ncit 2, :string "Collective Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. In this paper, we propose a new variant of Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA): Collective LDA (C-LDA), for multiple corpora modeling. C-LDA combines multiple corpora during learning such that it can transfer knowledge from one corpus to another; meanwhile it keeps a discriminative node which represents the corpus ID to constrain the learned topics in each corpus. Compared with LDA locally applied to the target corpus, C-LDA results in refined topic-word distribution, while compared with applying LDA globally and straightforwardly to the combined corpus, C-LDA keeps each topic only for one corpus. We demonstrate that C-LDA has improved performance with these advantages by experiments on several benchmark document data sets.", :doc-id "Collective Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2008  ,  ,  "}, 2837105 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2837105, :key "conf/icassp/ChangC09", :title "Latent Dirichlet learning for document summarization.", :abstract "Automatic summarization is developed to extract the representative contents or sentences from a large corpus of documents. This paper presents a new hierarchical representation of words, sentences and documents in a corpus, and infers the Dirichlet distributions for latent topics and latent themes in word level and sentence level, respectively. The sentence-based latent Dirichlet allocation (SLDA) is accordingly established for document summarization. Different from the vector space summarization, SLDA is built to fit the fine structure of text documents, and is specifically designed for sentence selection. SLDA acts as a sentence mixture model with a mixture of Dirichlet themes, which are used to generate the latent topics in observed words. The theme model is inherent to distinguish sentences in a summarization system. In the experiments, the proposed SLDA outperforms other methods for document summarization in terms of precision, recall and F-measure.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 640995, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Ying-Lang Chang"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 999321, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jen-Tzung Chien"}), :year 2009, :venue "ICASSP", :ncit 19, :string "Latent Dirichlet learning for document summarization.. Automatic summarization is developed to extract the representative contents or sentences from a large corpus of documents. This paper presents a new hierarchical representation of words, sentences and documents in a corpus, and infers the Dirichlet distributions for latent topics and latent themes in word level and sentence level, respectively. The sentence-based latent Dirichlet allocation (SLDA) is accordingly established for document summarization. Different from the vector space summarization, SLDA is built to fit the fine structure of text documents, and is specifically designed for sentence selection. SLDA acts as a sentence mixture model with a mixture of Dirichlet themes, which are used to generate the latent topics in observed words. The theme model is inherent to distinguish sentences in a summarization system. In the experiments, the proposed SLDA outperforms other methods for document summarization in terms of precision, recall and F-measure.", :doc-id "Latent Dirichlet learning for document summarization. 2009  ,  "}, 3663601 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3663601, :key "conf/icpr/CaoL12", :title "Type-2 fuzzy labeled latent Dirichlet allocation for human action categorization.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 462919, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Xiao-Qin Cao"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 290164, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Zhi-Qiang Liu"}), :year 2012, :venue "ICPR", :ncit 0, :string "Type-2 fuzzy labeled latent Dirichlet allocation for human action categorization.. ", :doc-id "Type-2 fuzzy labeled latent Dirichlet allocation for human action categorization. 2012  ,  "}, 3393393 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3393393, :key "journals/ida/Olszewski12", :title "Employing Kullback-Leibler divergence and Latent Dirichlet Allocation for fraud detection in telecommunications.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14101026, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Dominik Olszewski"}), :year 2012, :venue "Intell. Data Anal.", :ncit 0, :string "Employing Kullback-Leibler divergence and Latent Dirichlet Allocation for fraud detection in telecommunications.. ", :doc-id "Employing Kullback-Leibler divergence and Latent Dirichlet Allocation for fraud detection in telecommunications. 2012  "}, 2795730 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2795730, :key "conf/icmcs/VretosNP09", :title "A perceptual hashing algorithm using latent dirichlet allocation.", :abstract "This paper investigates the possibility of extracting latent aspects of a video, using visual information about humans (e.g. actors' faces), in order to develop a fingerprinting (replica detection) framework. We employ a generative probabilistic model, namely Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA), so as to capture latent aspects of a video, using facial semantic information derived from the video. We use the bag-of-words concept, (bag-of-faces in our case) in order to ensure exchangeability of the latent variables (e.g. topics). The video topics are modeled as a mixture of distributions of faces in each video. This generative probabilistic model has already been used in the case of text modeling with good results. Experimental results provide evidence that the proposed method performs very efficiently for video fingerprinting.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 917344, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Nicholas Vretos"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1043356, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Nikos Nikolaidis"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 175341, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Ioannis Pitas"}), :year 2009, :venue "ICME", :ncit 0, :string "A perceptual hashing algorithm using latent dirichlet allocation.. This paper investigates the possibility of extracting latent aspects of a video, using visual information about humans (e.g. actors' faces), in order to develop a fingerprinting (replica detection) framework. We employ a generative probabilistic model, namely Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA), so as to capture latent aspects of a video, using facial semantic information derived from the video. We use the bag-of-words concept, (bag-of-faces in our case) in order to ensure exchangeability of the latent variables (e.g. topics). The video topics are modeled as a mixture of distributions of faces in each video. This generative probabilistic model has already been used in the case of text modeling with good results. Experimental results provide evidence that the proposed method performs very efficiently for video fingerprinting.", :doc-id "A perceptual hashing algorithm using latent dirichlet allocation. 2009  ,  ,  "}, 701650 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 701650, :key "conf/airweb/BiroSSB09", :title "Linked latent Dirichlet allocation in web spam filtering.", :abstract "Latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA) (Blei, Ng, Jordan 2003) is a fully generative statistical language model on the content and topics of a corpus of documents. In this paper we apply an extension of LDA for web spam classification. Our linked LDA technique takes also linkage into account: topics are propagated along links in such a way that the linked document directly influences the words in the linking document. The inferred LDA model can be applied for classification as dimensionality reduction similarly to latent semantic indexing. We test linked LDA on the WEBSPAM-UK2007 corpus. By using BayesNet classifier, in terms of the AUC of classification, we achieve 3% improvement over plain LDA with BayesNet, and 8% over the public link features with C4.5. The addition of this method to a log-odds based combination of strong link and content baseline classifiers results in a 3% improvement in AUC. Our method even slightly improves over the best Web Spam Challenge 2008 result.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1532256, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "István Bíró"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1276256, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Dávid Siklósi"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 559961, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jácint Szabó"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 510808, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "András A. Benczúr"}), :year 2009, :venue "AIRWeb", :ncit 22, :string "Linked latent Dirichlet allocation in web spam filtering.. Latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA) (Blei, Ng, Jordan 2003) is a fully generative statistical language model on the content and topics of a corpus of documents. In this paper we apply an extension of LDA for web spam classification. Our linked LDA technique takes also linkage into account: topics are propagated along links in such a way that the linked document directly influences the words in the linking document. The inferred LDA model can be applied for classification as dimensionality reduction similarly to latent semantic indexing. We test linked LDA on the WEBSPAM-UK2007 corpus. By using BayesNet classifier, in terms of the AUC of classification, we achieve 3% improvement over plain LDA with BayesNet, and 8% over the public link features with C4.5. The addition of this method to a log-odds based combination of strong link and content baseline classifiers results in a 3% improvement in AUC. Our method even slightly improves over the best Web Spam Challenge 2008 result.", :doc-id "Linked latent Dirichlet allocation in web spam filtering. 2009  ,  ,  ,  "}, 514962 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 514962, :key "conf/nips/BleiNJ01", :title "Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract "We describe latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA), a generative probabilistic model for collections of discrete data such as text corpora. LDA is a three-level hierarchical Bayesian model, in which each item of a collection is modeled as a finite mixture over an underlying set of topics. Each topic is, in turn, modeled as an infinite mixture over an underlying set of topic probabilities. In the context of text modeling, the topic probabilities provide an explicit representation of a document. We present efficient approximate inference techniques based on variational methods and an EM algorithm for empirical Bayes parameter estimation. We report results in document modeling, text classification, and collaborative filtering, comparing to a mixture of unigrams model and the probabilistic LSI model.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 264481, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "David M. Blei"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 123223, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Andrew Y. Ng"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 221919, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Michael I. Jordan"}), :year 2001, :venue "NIPS", :ncit 6625, :string "Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. We describe latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA), a generative probabilistic model for collections of discrete data such as text corpora. LDA is a three-level hierarchical Bayesian model, in which each item of a collection is modeled as a finite mixture over an underlying set of topics. Each topic is, in turn, modeled as an infinite mixture over an underlying set of topic probabilities. In the context of text modeling, the topic probabilities provide an explicit representation of a document. We present efficient approximate inference techniques based on variational methods and an EM algorithm for empirical Bayes parameter estimation. We report results in document modeling, text classification, and collaborative filtering, comparing to a mixture of unigrams model and the probabilistic LSI model.", :doc-id "Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2001  ,  ,  "}, 3241363 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3241363, :key "conf/nips/PettersonSCBN10", :title "Word Features for Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1094364, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "James Petterson"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14157984, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Alexander J. Smola"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 844292, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Tibério S. Caetano"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1075369, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Wray L. Buntine"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1580079, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Shravan Narayanamurthy"}), :year 2010, :venue "NIPS", :ncit 8, :string "Word Features for Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. ", :doc-id "Word Features for Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2010  ,  ,  ,  ,  "}, 3241268 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3