round modern information retrieval (IR) models such as latent semantic indexing (LSI); however, latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA), a modular and extensible IR model, has significant advantages over both LSI and probabilistic LSI (pLSI). In this paper we present an LDA-based static technique for automating bug localization. We describe the implementation of our technique and three case studies that measure its effectiveness. For two of the case studies we directly compare our results to those from similar studies performed using LSI. The results demonstrate our LDA-based technique performs at least as well as the LSI-based techniques for all bugs and performs better, often significantly so, than the LSI-based techniques for most bugs.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 266985, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Stacy K. Lukins"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 559655, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Nicholas A. Kraft"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 594763, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Letha H. Etzkorn"}), :year 2008, :venue "WCRE", :ncit 65, :string "Source Code Retrieval for Bug Localization Using Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. In bug localization, a developer uses information about a bug to locate the portion of the source code to modify to correct the bug. Developers expend considerable effort performing this task. Some recent static techniques for automatic bug localization have been built around modern information retrieval (IR) models such as latent semantic indexing (LSI); however, latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA), a modular and extensible IR model, has significant advantages over both LSI and probabilistic LSI (pLSI). In this paper we present an LDA-based static technique for automating bug localization. We describe the implementation of our technique and three case studies that measure its effectiveness. For two of the case studies we directly compare our results to those from similar studies performed using LSI. The results demonstrate our LDA-based technique performs at least as well as the LSI-based techniques for all bugs and performs better, often significantly so, than the LSI-based techniques for most bugs.", :doc-id "Source Code Retrieval for Bug Localization Using Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2008  ,  ,  "}, 3336088 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3336088, :key "conf/wocc/ChenT11", :title "Evaluating effectiveness of Latent Dirichlet Allocation model for scene classification.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14092351, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Shizhi Chen"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1033098, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yingli Tian"}), :year 2011, :venue "WOCC", :ncit 0, :string "Evaluating effectiveness of Latent Dirichlet Allocation model for scene classification.. ", :doc-id "Evaluating effectiveness of Latent Dirichlet Allocation model for scene classification. 2011  ,  "}, 3041657 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3041657, :key "conf/interspeech/ChuehC09", :title "Nonstationary latent Dirichlet allocation for speech recognition.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 972698, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Chuang-Hua Chueh"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 999321, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jen-Tzung Chien"}), :year 2009, :venue "INTERSPEECH", :ncit 8, :string "Nonstationary latent Dirichlet allocation for speech recognition.. ", :doc-id "Nonstationary latent Dirichlet allocation for speech recognition. 2009  ,  "}, 1326489 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1326489, :key "conf/wsdm/AgarwalC10", :title "fLDA: matrix factorization through latent dirichlet allocation.", :abstract "We propose fLDA, a novel matrix factorization method to predict ratings in recommender system applications where a \"bag-of-words\" representation for item meta-data is natural. Such scenarios are commonplace in web applications like content recommendation, ad targeting and web search where items are articles, ads and web pages respectively. Because of data sparseness, regularization is key to good predictive accuracy. Our method works by regularizing both user and item factors simultaneously through user features and the bag of words associated with each item. Specifically, each word in an item is associated with a discrete latent factor often referred to as the topic of the word; item topics are obtained by averaging topics across all words in an item. Then, user rating on an item is modeled as user's affinity to the item's topics where user affinity to topics (user factors) and topic assignments to words in items (item factors) are learned jointly in a supervised fashion. To avoid overfitting, user and item factors are regularized through Gaussian linear regression and Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) priors respectively. We show our model is accurate, interpretable and handles both cold-start and warm-start scenarios seamlessly through a single model. The efficacy of our method is illustrated on benchmark datasets and a new dataset from Yahoo! Buzz where fLDA provides superior predictive accuracy in cold-start scenarios and is comparable to state-of-the-art methods in warm-start scenarios. As a by-product, fLDA also identifies interesting topics that explains user-item interactions. Our method also generalizes a recently proposed technique called supervised LDA (sLDA) to collaborative filtering applications. While sLDA estimates item topic vectors in a supervised fashion for a single regression, fLDA incorporates multiple regressions (one for each user) in estimating the item factors.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1080450, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Deepak Agarwal"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1013676, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Bee-Chung Chen"}), :year 2010, :venue "WSDM", :ncit 45, :string "fLDA: matrix factorization through latent dirichlet allocation.. We propose fLDA, a novel matrix factorization method to predict ratings in recommender system applications where a \"bag-of-words\" representation for item meta-data is natural. Such scenarios are commonplace in web applications like content recommendation, ad targeting and web search where items are articles, ads and web pages respectively. Because of data sparseness, regularization is key to good predictive accuracy. Our method works by regularizing both user and item factors simultaneously through user features and the bag of words associated with each item. Specifically, each word in an item is associated with a discrete latent factor often referred to as the topic of the word; item topics are obtained by averaging topics across all words in an item. Then, user rating on an item is modeled as user's affinity to the item's topics where user affinity to topics (user factors) and topic assignments to words in items (item factors) are learned jointly in a supervised fashion. To avoid overfitting, user and item factors are regularized through Gaussian linear regression and Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) priors respectively. We show our model is accurate, interpretable and handles both cold-start and warm-start scenarios seamlessly through a single model. The efficacy of our method is illustrated on benchmark datasets and a new dataset from Yahoo! Buzz where fLDA provides superior predictive accuracy in cold-start scenarios and is comparable to state-of-the-art methods in warm-start scenarios. As a by-product, fLDA also identifies interesting topics that explains user-item interactions. Our method also generalizes a recently proposed technique called supervised LDA (sLDA) to collaborative filtering applications. While sLDA estimates item topic vectors in a supervised fashion for a single regression, fLDA incorporates multiple regressions (one for each user) in estimating the item factors.", :doc-id "fLDA: matrix factorization through latent dirichlet allocation. 2010  ,  "}, 206489 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 206489, :key "conf/fintal/KakkonenMS06", :title "Applying Latent Dirichlet Allocation to Automatic Essay Grading.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 24559, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Tuomo Kakkonen"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 341597, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Niko Myller"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 200379, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Erkki Sutinen"}), :year 2006, :venue "FinTAL", :ncit 12, :string "Applying Latent Dirichlet Allocation to Automatic Essay Grading.. ", :doc-id "Applying Latent Dirichlet Allocation to Automatic Essay Grading. 2006  ,  ,  "}, 3172025 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3172025, :key "conf/oss/PrattMKR11", :title "Cliff Walls: An Analysis of Monolithic Commits Using Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14170416, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Landon J. Pratt"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1415091, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Alexander C. MacLean"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 616968, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Charles D. Knutson"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 994142, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Eric K. Ringger"}), :year 2011, :venue "OSS", :ncit 4, :string "Cliff Walls: An Analysis of Monolithic Commits Using Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. ", :doc-id "Cliff Walls: An Analysis of Monolithic Commits Using Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2011  ,  ,  ,  "}, 3443930 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3443930, :key "conf/nips/PerotteWEB11", :title "Hierarchically Supervised Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1418190, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Adler J. Perotte"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1447158, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Frank Wood"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1147269, :firs