res in large real-world graph data. Existing Bayesian approaches for group discovery (such as Infinite Relational Models) have only been applied to small graphs with a couple of hundred nodes. LDA-G (short for Latent Dirichlet Allocation for Graphs) utilizes a well-known topic modeling algorithm to find latent group structure. Specifically, we modify Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) to operate on graph data instead of text corpora. Our modifications reflect the differences between real-world graph data and text corpora (e.g., a node's neighbor count vs. a document's word count). In our empirical study, we apply LDA-G to several large graphs (with thousands of nodes) from PubMed (a scientific publication repository). We compare LDA-G's quantitative performance on link prediction with two existing approaches: one Bayesian (namely, Infinite Relational Model) and one non-Bayesian (namely, Cross-association). On average, LDA-G outperforms IRM by 15% and Cross-association by 25% (in terms of area under the ROC curve). Furthermore, we demonstrate that LDA-G can discover useful qualitative information.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 410063, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Keith Henderson"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 806969, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Tina Eliassi-Rad"}), :year 2009, :venue "SAC", :ncit 19, :string "Applying latent dirichlet allocation to group discovery in large graphs.. This paper introduces LDA-G, a scalable Bayesian approach to finding latent group structures in large real-world graph data. Existing Bayesian approaches for group discovery (such as Infinite Relational Models) have only been applied to small graphs with a couple of hundred nodes. LDA-G (short for Latent Dirichlet Allocation for Graphs) utilizes a well-known topic modeling algorithm to find latent group structure. Specifically, we modify Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) to operate on graph data instead of text corpora. Our modifications reflect the differences between real-world graph data and text corpora (e.g., a node's neighbor count vs. a document's word count). In our empirical study, we apply LDA-G to several large graphs (with thousands of nodes) from PubMed (a scientific publication repository). We compare LDA-G's quantitative performance on link prediction with two existing approaches: one Bayesian (namely, Infinite Relational Model) and one non-Bayesian (namely, Cross-association). On average, LDA-G outperforms IRM by 15% and Cross-association by 25% (in terms of area under the ROC curve). Furthermore, we demonstrate that LDA-G can discover useful qualitative information.", :doc-id "Applying latent dirichlet allocation to group discovery in large graphs. 2009  ,  "}, 517979 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 517979, :key "conf/nips/WangG07", :title "Spatial Latent Dirichlet Allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 660704, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Xiaogang Wang"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1401746, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Eric Grimson"}), :year 2007, :venue "NIPS", :ncit 106, :string "Spatial Latent Dirichlet Allocation.. ", :doc-id "Spatial Latent Dirichlet Allocation. 2007  ,  "}, 3024924 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3024924, :key "conf/jcdl/PanM11", :title "Event detection with spatial latent Dirichlet allocation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1128805, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Chi-Chun Pan"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1462446, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Prasenjit Mitra"}), :year 2011, :venue "JCDL", :ncit 3, :string "Event detection with spatial latent Dirichlet allocation.. ", :doc-id "Event detection with spatial latent Dirichlet allocation. 2011  ,  "}, 3697853 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3697853, :key "journals/ieicet/ToraE13", :title "MPI/OpenMP Hybrid Parallel Inference Methods for Latent Dirichlet Allocation - Approximati